abstract = {Moisture is transported in South America westward from the tropical$\backslash$nAtlantic Ocean to the Amazon basin, and then southward toward the$\backslash$nextratropics. A regional intensification of this circulation to the$\backslash$neast of the Andes Mountains is called the South American low-level$\backslash$njet (SALLJ), with the strongest winds found over eastern Bolivia.$\backslash$nSALLJ is present all year and channels moisture to the La Plata basin,$\backslash$nwhich is analogous to the better-known Amazon basin in terms of its$\backslash$nbiological and habitat diversity, and far exceeds the latter in its$\backslash$neconomic importance to southern and central South America in terms$\backslash$nof hydroelectricity and food production. The relatively small SALLJ$\backslash$nspatial scale (compared with the density of the available sounding$\backslash$nnetwork) has a limited understanding of and modeling capability for$\backslash$nany variations in the SALLJ intensity and structure as well as its$\backslash$npossible relationship to downstream rainfall. The SALLJ Experiment$\backslash$n(SALLJEX), aimed at describing many aspects of SALLJ, was carried$\backslash$nout between 15 November 2002 and 15 February 2003 in Bolivia, Paraguay,$\backslash$ncentral and northern Argentina, western Brazil, and Peru. Scientists,$\backslash$ncollaborators, students, National Meteorological Service personnel,$\backslash$nand local volunteers from South American countries and the United$\backslash$nStates participated in SALLJEX activities in an unprecedented way,$\backslash$nbecause SALLJEX was the most extensive meteorological field activity$\backslash$nto date in subtropical South America, and was the first World Climate$\backslash$nResearch Program/Climate Variability and Prediction Program international$\backslash$ncampaign in South America. This paper describes the motivation for$\backslash$nthe field activity in the region, the special SALLJEX observations,$\backslash$nand SALLJEX modeling and outreach activities. We also describe some$\backslash$npreliminary scientific conclusions and discuss some of the remaining$\backslash$nquestions.},
